 E.\nMoore. Phoenix: C. C. Duke, San\nFrancisco: Mr. and Mrs. M. T.\nMoyer. Kansas City. Mo.; B. M. Hill.\nPhoenix; R. H. Topping. Phoenix;\nJ W Tardy and wife. Phoenix; E.\nU. Wheelock. Los Angeles; W. F.\nJones. Benson; Susain Montain.\nNacozari.\nEIGHTEEN NATIONS FORM\nSTANDARDS ASSOCIATION\nWASHINGTON \u2014To promote\nuniformity of national standards\nand to exchange information on\nstandardization work in different\ncountries, an International standards\nassociation has been organized.\nThe association, with member\ngroups In 18 countries, should re\nsuit in great benefits to all nations\nconcerned, says George K. Burgess,\ndirector of the bureau of standards.\n\u201cScience standards form the basis\nof countless kinds of measure\nments,\u201d Mr. Hughes points out.\n\u201cSuch measurements may begin in\nthe laboratory. They graduate into\nindustry. A measuring device at\ni first a novelty of the laboratory\nmay later control ths process of a\ngiant industry.\u201d\n\nDispatch Telephones\u2014Bl-82.\nMEATS\nThe Best at\nLowest Prices\nQTUAVQ Beef, Loin, Round\niLnAd and T-Bones, 90\nPound JOC\nBEEF CHUCK ROAST, lb 25c\nPRIME RIB ROAST, lb 27c\nHamburger\nFresh\nPound .20C\nBEEF LIVER, lb 25c\nVEAL. Round, Loin, T-Bone\nand Chops, lb 40c\nVEAL CHUCK ROAST, lb. 25c\nVEAL SHOULDER ROAST.\nlb ...l- 27c\nVEAL LIVER, lb. 40c\nPORK LOIN\nCHOPS\nPound 35c\nPork Shoulder\nROAST\nPound 28c\nPORK SAUSAGE, lb 25c\nRATH\u2019S BACON, by the Piece,\nlb. 30c\nRATH\u2019S SLICED BACON, lb. 45c\nPEYTON\u2019S SLICED BACON,\nlb. 40c\nBONELESS HAM BUTTS. Ib. 38c\nPOTATO SALAD. Home-Made.\nlb. Me\nCHICKEN PIES, Home-Made,\neach 25c\nVEAL PIES. Home-Made, each 20c\nAlabama Girls Get Life Terms\no\u00ab Im w I\nIMi >&'\u2014Qi MH s\nMB\n\nSKA Hirutingham Hunan\nConvicted of the murder of Harry Cunningham. Scottsboro, Ala.,\nfarmer, these two xirls have just begun serving life sentences in the\nState women's prison at Wetumpka. Myrtle Graham, 17, right, ad\nmitted stabbing Cunningham while Newby Moatea. 19. left, present\nat the time, was held as nn accessory. She elc\u00ab!ed to rlaud liiul\nwith her friend and uhare her fats.\nBusiness Good,\nSay Steel Men\nExecutives at American\nInstitute Satisfied With\nConditions.\nNEW YORK. May 9 ^\u2022'\u2014Execu\ntives of the American steel in\ndustry. in exchanging views at a\nmeeting of the American Iron\nSteel Institute, agreed today that\nthe present business situation is\nfa voluble, with better times just\nCharles M. Schwab, president of\nthe institute and chairman of\nBethlethem Steel; James A. Far\nrell, president of United States\nSteel; Horace S. Wilkinson, presi\ndent of Crucible Steel, and other\nheads of steel companies all indi\ncated tliat the present weaker price\ntendencies nad reduced operations\nlooked important only in comparison\nwith the record breaking produc\ntion and better prices of a year\nago.\n\u201cLooking back over the last de\ncade. you will find that our present\nrate of operations has always been\nregarded in the past as a most\nsatisfactory rate; therefore our rate\ntoday should be considered as\nequally satisfactory.' said Mr.\nSchwab.\nPredicting that the second 1930\nquarter would be better than the\nfirst, Mr. Schwab, whose corpora\ntion recently arranged a merger\nwith the Youngstown Sheet Tube\ncompany, said each proposed merger\nmust justify itself.\n\u201cWhere a merger,\" he said,\ndsmonstrably results in better di\nversification. greater industrial\nstability and efficiency, and gives\nto the public greater or better fa\n-1 cilities for supplying Its needs, there\nit is legitimate and will succeed.\nAnd in such instances it deserves\ni the fullest public encouragement.\"\nMr. Farrell, in discussing the\nsam*e problems, said he thought\n\u201cthe bloom is off the rose in tne\nmerger business\n\u2019To merge or not to merge\u2014\nthat is the question.\u201d he saia.\nI \"Some think that unless we merge\nSpecials-Saturday and Monday\nBEEF RIB\nSTEW\nPound 20c\nPORK HAM\nROAST\n33c\nPound\nLARD\nRath\u2019s Pure\n2 Pounds 30c\nDOUGLAS DAILY DISPATCH. SATURDAY MORNING, MAY 10, 1930\nCI If* AD Pure Cane, in Cloth Bags,\nuUuZUV 5 Pounds\nCOFFEE P k 37c\nCREEN BEANS 25c\nLETTUCE K H 5c\nCUCUMBERS S s 5c\nI\u00a37 I A Assorted Flavors,\nJLLLU3 Packages\napples 10c\npip f Bulk, Full Heads, 97\niULL 4 Pounds C\nOVALTINE 87c\nSWEET POTATOES 25c\npnf)|firQ Fresh Shipment, Mer- fO\nCvvlllEm chants\u2019, Assorted, 2 Pounds\nADDIPfbTC ^ancy, 12-Ounce 97_\nAl illL VI O Package, Each LI C\nCELERY ST 15c\nCORN MEAL S\u2019\" B s 42c\nPP^VP* Monte, Medium Size, OP\nIIIUIIEO 2-Pound Package, Each vUC\nSmith\u2019s\nGrocery Market\nPERRY R. SMITH\n1950 A Avenue Phones: 293-78-1'\nwe will be submerged. But the best\ntMBf vm can do Is to emerge. I\nthink people will make as much\nmoney out of what they have as\nthey will out of what they expect\nto get.'\u2019\nTom L. Gtrdier, chairman and\npresident of Republic Steel, and L,\nE. Block, chairman of Inland Steel,\nboth expressed favorable views re\ngarding the business outlook. George\nM. Verity, chairman of the Amer\nican Rolling Milks company, pre\ndicted a \"conservatively active\nyear.\"\nLEIPSIG <**>\u2014lmitating the man\nufacturer of artificial honey who\nput a dead bee in each jar to make\nIt look natural, an exhibitor al the\nfair lie\u00bb-e shows a machine for\nprinting circulars which overprints\nsome characters to make them look\nlike real typewriter errors.\nk Jnce W\nUPON\nA TIME,-^\nBenito Musso\nlinl. now dicta-\ntor of Italy, was\na hodcarrier In 91\nSwitzerland It\nwas his first lob\nafter ha tired of\nteaching school\nand began the\nlife of wander-\ning that\nthe premiership w\nof hi* country. f\nitaiiiM Aw\nTombstone High School Graduates VS in\nPresident's tip for Second Time With\nHigh Freshman Glass Average at \u2018U\u2019\nc\nA large audience present at the\nhigh school auditorium Monday\nafternoon r aw Dr. Walker of the\nUniversity of Arizona, present the\npresident's cup to the Tombstone\nnigh school. Di. Walker, who has\nspent 15 years in high school work,\nexpressed great pleasure in being\nselect\u2019d by President Schantz to de\nliver this cup to Tombstone. The\nstudents whe .e names are engraved\nthereon arc Miss Ruth James. Miss\nLcuise Huff and Rex Knoles. all\nmembers of the class of 1928. These\nyount; )>coplc made the highest aver\na(c ol any school in the state during\ntheir freshman year at the univer\nsity.\nThis is the second time the cup\nhas been awarded to Tombstone,\nbeing won in 1922-23 by Camilla\nDalgleish. Rhese Cornelius, Norma\nBarr and Cornelia Cornelius. The\niirst year this cup was given the\nhonor went to Prescott, and in suc\ncession to Tombstone. Chandler,\nAjo. Salford. Nogales, Casa Grande,\nYuma, and now again to Tombstone,,\nthe only town in the state to have\nthat honor twice.\nDr. Walker\u2019s remarks were not\nconfined to the mental development\nof the youth of today, but verged a\nthree-fold development, mental,\nphysical and spiritual. He spoke of\nthe first emblem which he ever wore,\nan equilateral triangle, in other\nwords, the emblem of the Y. M.\nC. A., which represents the three\nfold nature of man. The cups for\nmental and physical supremacy\nwere both in evidence, the first be\ning a reward to our students in\nTucson, and the other being won\nat a track meet held in Benson\ntwo weeks ago, signifying the phy\nsical development of our student\nbody The third cup was likened to\nthe Holy Grail, for which men\n'ought and died in earlier history.\nTills invisible cup they will also\nstrive to secure by living clean moral\nlives.\nDr.-Walker was followed by Coach\nL. L. Ledford, who congratulated\nthe school on the high averages of\nits former students, also his own\nI boys who in the athletic field\nfought against great odds, with\nonly a small number to represent\nthe school. In football he had just\n11 boys aU through every game, and\nreceived much publicity in the news\npapers on that account, as the only\nteam in which the original 11 men\nplayed every game of the season\nwithout substitutes. In basketball,\nbaseball and track, the same boys\nfeatured.\nThe track team consisted of Joe\nDalgleish, captain; Walter Willcox,\nTalmadge Ijams, Jimmie Giacolettl,\nHoward Wynn. Marcel Saunders,\nChappie Macia and Eddie Knoles.\nThese boys won the class \u201cB\" cham-\npionship in baseball, and will re-\nceive that cup also, within the week. I\nJoe Dalgleish in a short speech ac- j\ncepted both cups in behalf of the\nseniors, thanking Dr. Walker and j\nCoach Ledford, who presented them.\nHe then passed them to Miss Kath\nerine Kitchell. of the junior class,\ncharging her to guard them well. 1\nBOLOGNA, lb 25c\nW RATH\u2019S\nHams ?w\u00ab r\nibs., ib. ..Oil\nCOTTAGE CHEESE, 8-Ounce\nPackage, each 15c\nBUTTER, Maricopa, lb 49c\nBUTTER, Brookfield, lb 48c\nNUCOA, lb 25c\nPLYMOUTH ROCK\nUPNQ A,ive ,b 35c\nnElld Dressed, Ib 38c\nYEAST, Fleischman\u2019s, 6 Cakes 22c\nRHODE ISLAND RED\nrpvrpc Alive, lb. 42c\nFll l LitO Dressed, lb 45c\nCANADIAN BACON, While It\nLasts, Ib 45c\nrPPC Guaranteed QO\nLUU J Fresh. 3 Dozen .JpLvO\nPeyton\u2019s Baby Beef Used\nReady to Sell at 11 A. M.\nBarbecued in Our Screened-in\nBARBECUE\nBarbecue Pit\nlb. 50c\nShe in turn handed them to Marcel\nSaunders, sophomore, who presented\nthem to Mildred Moore, freshman.\nBeth Rose Macia accepted them for\nthe grammar schools.\nEach student who took part in the\nceremony made short speeches of\nacceptance and thanks, promising\non behaif of their class to live up\nto the high standards set by the\nschool and to ket p ever untarnished\nthe bright silver cups.\nThe program ended with a selec\ntion by the high school band. Prof.\nTilford and his music students en\ntertained with four numbers which\nwe-e highly appreciated by the\naudience.\nHILCHENBACH. Westphalia\nWas 28C German poets, statesmen\nand other leaders have thought\nabout hiking as a national sports is\n.set forth 